\section{Near-Reference Restricted Adaptation}
\label{sec:near_reference_restricted}
We study near-reference adaptation in which a strong reference checkpoint $\theta_0$ is adapted to improve supervised fine-tuning (SFT)
while limiting functional drift from the reference model.
Let $\pi_\theta(\cdot|x)$ denote the model distribution. We measure drift by
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{x}\Big[\mathrm{KL}\big(\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x)\ \|\ \pi_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x)\big)\Big],
\label{eq:dref_def}
\end{equation}
and optimize the SFT objective
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y^*)\sim\mathcal{D}}[-\log \pi_{\theta}(y^*|x)].
\label{eq:tsft_def}
\end{equation}
We treat $D_{\mathrm{ref}}$ as a drift measurement; when reasoning about near-reference trade-offs, it is convenient to view adaptation under a drift budget
$D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le\delta$.
\subsection{AS-LST: the restricted update class}
\label{subsec:as_lst_clean}
\paragraph{Anchoring and segmental layers.}
Let $\mathcal E$ denote the parameters of the input embedding and output embedding (LM head).\footnote{If tied, $\mathcal E$ denotes the tied weights.}
We anchor them by
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\mathcal E}\ \equiv\ \theta_{0,\mathcal E}.
\label{eq:anchor_emb_head}
\end{equation}
We select trainable transformer blocks $M$ as the union of two contiguous segments,
\begin{equation}
M\ =\ M_{\mathrm{low}}\cup M_{\mathrm{high}},
\qquad M_{\mathrm{low}},M_{\mathrm{high}}\ \text{contiguous},
\label{eq:segmental_M}
\end{equation}
and freeze all other parameters:
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\neg(M\cup \mathcal E)}\ \equiv\ \theta_{0,\neg(M\cup \mathcal E)}.
\label{eq:as_lst_freeze}
\end{equation}
We refer to \eqref{eq:anchor_emb_head}--\eqref{eq:as_lst_freeze} as \emph{anchored segmental LST (AS-LST)}.
\paragraph{Two-stage schedule.}
Within the same AS-LST feasible set, we consider two solver choices:
\emph{joint} training updates $(M_{\mathrm{low}},M_{\mathrm{high}})$ throughout,
while a \emph{two-stage} schedule first updates $M_{\mathrm{low}}$ (freezing $M_{\mathrm{high}}$) and then updates $M_{\mathrm{high}}$
starting from the stage-1 checkpoint.
\subsection{A single organizing object: drift-normalized local adaptation}
\label{subsec:local_proxy_clean}
Our goal is reliable task improvement under near-reference drift. We therefore study, within the AS-LST subspace, the best \emph{local} SFT decrease achievable per unit drift.
Let $g:=\nabla\mathcal T(\theta)\vert_{\theta_0}$ and $g_M$ its restriction to $M$.
\paragraph{Near-reference approximation.}
In a small neighborhood of $\theta_0$ we use the first-order expansion
$\mathcal T(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)\approx \mathcal T(\theta_0)+g^\top\Delta\theta$.
For drift, a second-order expansion of KL yields the Fisher quadratic form
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)\ \approx\ \frac12\,\Delta\theta^\top F\,\Delta\theta,
\label{eq:fisher_quad}
\end{equation}
where $F$ is the Fisher information of $\pi_{\theta_0}$ under the same input distribution as \eqref{eq:dref_def}
(derivation in Appendix). Under AS-LST, $\Delta\theta_{\mathcal E}=0$ and $\Delta\theta_{\neg(M\cup\mathcal E)}=0$,
so the drift reduces to $\frac12\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\Delta\theta_M$ with $F_M:=F_{MM}$.
\paragraph{Local drift-budgeted subproblem.}
The near-reference trade-off is captured by the drift-budgeted local subproblem
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Delta\theta_M}\ g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
\frac12\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\Delta\theta_M\le \delta,
\label{eq:local_trust_region}
\end{equation}
which formalizes ``largest first-order SFT decrease under drift budget $\delta$ within AS-LST''.
\begin{proposition}[AS-LST drift-normalized improvement]
\label{prop:as_lst_local_value}
Assume $F_M\succ 0$. The optimal value of \eqref{eq:local_trust_region} is
\begin{equation}
\min \eqref{eq:local_trust_region}
\ =\
-\sqrt{2\delta}\,\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}},
\qquad
\|\upsilon\|_{F_M^{-1}}^2:=\upsilon^\top F_M^{-1}\upsilon,
\label{eq:local_value}
\end{equation}
achieved by $\Delta\theta_M \propto -F_M^{-1}g_M$.
\end{proposition}
\noindent
Proposition~\ref{prop:as_lst_local_value} yields a direct segment-selection signal: choose $(M_{\mathrm{low}},M_{\mathrm{high}})$ that maximize
$\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}}$ (in practice estimated by our dual-output probe).
\paragraph{Remark (full tuning is a capacity bound).}
The same local analysis can be carried out in the full space, giving the value $-\sqrt{2\delta}\|g\|_{F^{-1}}$.
This is a representational upper bound on drift-normalized improvement; our focus is the attainable improvement within AS-LST and how solver choices affect it.
\subsection{Two-stage vs.\ joint as solvers under the same local model}
\label{subsec:two_stage_clean}
We now compare two-stage and joint training through the same near-reference lens.
To model optimization difficulty beyond the first-order term, consider the local quadratic proxy
\begin{equation}
\Phi(\Delta\theta_M)
:=
g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
+\frac12 \Delta\theta_M^\top (H_M+\beta F_M)\Delta\theta_M,
\label{eq:phi_def}
\end{equation}
where $H_M$ is a local curvature matrix of $\mathcal T$ on $M$ and $\beta>0$ sets the drift scale.
Eq.~\eqref{eq:phi_def} is a standard second-order model of near-reference optimization within AS-LST.
Partition $\Delta\theta_M=(\Delta\theta_L,\Delta\theta_H)$ according to $(M_{\mathrm{low}},M_{\mathrm{high}})$ and write
$H_M+\beta F_M=\begin{psmallmatrix} A & C\\ C^\top & B\end{psmallmatrix}$.
\begin{proposition}[Coupling-controlled gain of a two-stage pass]
\label{prop:two_stage_gain}
Assume $A\succ 0$ and $B\succ 0$.
Let $\Delta_L^{\ast}:=\arg\min_{\Delta\theta_L}\Phi(\Delta\theta_L,0)$.
Optimizing $\Delta\theta_H$ with $\Delta\theta_L=\Delta_L^{\ast}$ fixed (one two-stage pass) decreases the proxy by
\begin{equation}
\Phi(\Delta_L^{\ast},0)-\min_{\Delta\theta_H}\Phi(\Delta_L^{\ast},\Delta\theta_H)
\ =\
\frac12 \big\|B^{-1/2}C^\top \Delta_L^{\ast}\big\|_2^2.
\label{eq:two_stage_gain}
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}
\noindent
Eq.~\eqref{eq:two_stage_gain} isolates the role of segment coupling: when $C$ is non-negligible,
a block schedule explicitly compensates for coupling induced by the lower-segment update.
This provides a near-reference optimization mechanism for why two-stage AS-LST can more reliably reach strong solutions than joint tuning,
while operating under the same anchoring and segment constraints.
