\section{Subset Selection under Near-Reference Drift}
\label{sec:subset_selection_drift}
We select trainable layer subsets for layer-selective tuning (LST) by comparing candidates at a \emph{matched}
function-space drift from a strong reference model $\pi_{\theta_0}$.
The section has a single organizing principle:
\begin{quote}
\emph{A subset $M$ is preferred if it yields larger task improvement at the same measured drift budget.}
\end{quote}
To make this comparison meaningful, we (i) define a drift axis in function space, (ii) fix endpoint coordinate systems so drift is comparable across $M$,
and (iii) use an early-stopped matched-drift scoring rule.
We additionally clarify the role of two-stage schedules: they are solver choices within a fixed feasible set, aimed at improving \emph{attainability}
(reducing restricted optimization error), not improving the oracle optimum.
\subsection{Drift as the comparison axis}
\label{subsec:drift_axis}
Let $\pi_\theta(\cdot|x)$ denote the model distribution over outputs given input $x$.
We measure functional drift from the reference model via
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{x}\Big[\mathrm{KL}\big(\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x)\ \|\ \pi_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x)\big)\Big].
\label{eq:dref_def_again}
\end{equation}
In a small neighborhood of $\theta_0$, the drift admits a local quadratic approximation
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)\ \approx\ \frac12\,\Delta\theta^\top F\,\Delta\theta,
\label{eq:kl_fisher_local}
\end{equation}
where $F$ is the Fisher information matrix of $\pi_{\theta_0}$ under the same input distribution as Eq.~\eqref{eq:dref_def_again}
(derivation in Appendix).
Eq.~\eqref{eq:kl_fisher_local} motivates using $D_{\mathrm{ref}}$ as a drift budget/axis: it corresponds to a local norm in function space.
\subsection{Fixed endpoints: comparable drift across subsets}
\label{subsec:fixed_endpoints}
Matched-drift comparison across different trainable subsets $M$ requires drift to be measured in a \emph{fixed} coordinate system.
If the input embedding or the output projection (LM head) is trainable, endpoint coordinate freedoms can obscure the interpretation of drift
and increase solver-dependent variability.
\paragraph{Output gauge freedom.}
For a decoder LM with hidden states $h_\theta(x,t)$ and output head $(W_{\mathrm{out}},b_{\mathrm{out}})$, training $W_{\mathrm{out}}$
admits near-invariant transformations
\begin{equation}
h_\theta(x,t)\ \mapsto\ h_\theta(x,t)A,
\qquad
W_{\mathrm{out}}\ \mapsto\ W_{\mathrm{out}}A^{-T},
\label{eq:output_gauge}
\end{equation}
for invertible $A$, which can preserve logits while inducing large parameter motion and poor conditioning.
Similarly, training the input embedding can change the representation basis at the input and be compensated downstream.
\paragraph{Default setting (fixed endpoints).}
We therefore freeze both the input embedding and the output projection (LM head) in our default setting.
This fixes (i) the lexical basis seen by the backbone and (ii) the vocabulary basis used for readout, so that drift measurements
primarily reflect backbone changes and are comparable across different subsets $M$.
\subsection{Drift diagnostics (backbone vs head)}
\label{subsec:drift_diagnostics}
\paragraph{Reference-head drift (default).}
With fixed endpoints, drift can be measured in a fixed readout basis.
Let $h_\theta(x,t)$ denote the final hidden state under teacher forcing, and let $(W_0,b_0)$ be the frozen output head from $\theta_0$.
Define the reference-head distribution
\begin{equation}
p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)
=\mathrm{softmax}\!\left(h_\theta(x,t)W_0^\top+b_0\right).
\label{eq:p_ref_head}
\end{equation}
We measure drift on a probe set $\mathcal{X}_{\mathrm{probe}}$ via
\begin{equation}
\widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
:=
\mathbb{E}_{x\in\mathcal{X}_{\mathrm{probe}},\,t}
\Big[
\mathrm{KL}\big(p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)\ \|\ p^0_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x,t)\big)
\Big].
\label{eq:D_ref_probe}
\end{equation}
Because the same frozen head is used for all candidates, $\widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}$ is directly comparable across different $M$.
\paragraph{Dual-output drift (optional).}
When the output head is trainable, raw output drift mixes backbone and head changes.
We separate these effects by evaluating the same hidden states under two heads:
\begin{equation}
p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)=\mathrm{softmax}\!\left(h_\theta(x,t)W_0^\top+b_0\right),
\qquad
p^\theta_\theta(\cdot|x,t)=\mathrm{softmax}\!\left(h_\theta(x,t)W_\theta^\top+b_\theta\right),
\label{eq:p_dual}
\end{equation}
and defining a head-induced mismatch measure
\begin{equation}
\widehat D_{\mathrm{dual}}(\theta)
:=
\mathbb{E}_{x\in\mathcal{X}_{\mathrm{probe}},\,t}
\Big[
\mathrm{JS}\big(p^\theta_\theta(\cdot|x,t)\ \|\ p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)\big)
\Big].
\label{eq:D_dual}
\end{equation}
In this setting, $\widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}$ isolates backbone-induced drift in a fixed readout basis, while
$\widehat D_{\mathrm{dual}}$ quantifies the additional change introduced by the trained head conditioned on the same backbone states.
\subsection{Matched-drift selection rule}
\label{subsec:subset_selection}
Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a candidate family of trainable subsets.
For each $M\in\mathcal{M}$, we run a short tuning trajectory $\{\theta^{(k)}(M)\}_{k\ge 0}$ from $\theta^{(0)}(M)=\theta_0$
where only parameters in $M$ are trainable (endpoints fixed in the default setting).
We stop when the measured drift reaches a preset budget $\delta$:
\begin{equation}
\tau(M)
\ :=\
\min\Big\{k\ge 0:\ \widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}\big(\theta^{(k)}(M)\big)\ \ge\ \delta\Big\}.
\label{eq:stopping_time_tau}
\end{equation}
We then score $M$ by its improvement on a held-out evaluation metric $\mathcal{E}(\theta)$ (lower is better) at matched drift:
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Score}(M;\delta)
\ :=\
\mathcal{E}(\theta_0)\ -\ \mathcal{E}\big(\theta^{(\tau(M))}(M)\big).
\label{eq:score_matched_drift}
\end{equation}
When the output head is trainable, we optionally discard candidates with large head-induced change by requiring
$\widehat D_{\mathrm{dual}}\big(\theta^{(\tau(M))}(M)\big)\le \delta_{\mathrm{dual}}$.
\paragraph{Interpretation via drift-normalized local descent (analysis).}
In the near-reference regime, matched-drift selection is consistent with comparing candidates by drift-normalized descent directions.
Let $g:=\nabla\mathcal{T}(\theta)\vert_{\theta_0}$ and let $g_M$ be its restriction to $M$.
Using the Fisher local metric in Eq.~\eqref{eq:kl_fisher_local}, the best \emph{first-order} decrease in $\mathcal T$ within subset $M$
under budget $\delta$ solves
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Delta\theta_M}\ g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
\frac12\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\Delta\theta_M\le \delta,
\label{eq:local_trust_region_M}
\end{equation}
whose optimal value is $-\sqrt{2\delta}\,\|g_M\|_{(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}}$ under a damped metric $F_M+\lambda I$
(details in Appendix). This motivates selecting candidates that achieve larger improvement at the same drift.
\subsection{Two-stage schedules: solver choice, not oracle improvement}
\label{subsec:two_stage_clean_rewrite}
Finally, we clarify the role of two-stage schedules.
Two-stage does not change the subset $M$ and therefore does not change the oracle best-achievable value within that subset.
Its purpose is to reduce \emph{restricted optimization error} under practical training.
\paragraph{A second-order proxy for solver behavior.}
To model optimization difficulty beyond the first-order term, we consider a local quadratic proxy on $M$,
\begin{equation}
\Phi(\Delta\theta_M)
:=
g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
+\frac12 \Delta\theta_M^\top (H_M+\beta(F_M+\lambda I))\Delta\theta_M,
\label{eq:phi_def_rewrite}
\end{equation}
where $H_M$ is a local curvature matrix on $M$, $\beta>0$ sets the drift scale, and $\lambda\ge 0$ is a damping term.
Let $M=M_{\mathrm{low}}\cup M_{\mathrm{high}}$ (two contiguous segments) and partition $\Delta\theta_M=(\Delta\theta_L,\Delta\theta_H)$.
Write $H_M+\beta(F_M+\lambda I)=\begin{psmallmatrix} A & C\\ C^\top & B\end{psmallmatrix}$.
\begin{proposition}[Coupling-induced correction captured by the second stage]
\label{prop:two_stage_rewrite}
Assume $A\succ 0$ and $B\succ 0$.
Let $\Delta_L^{\ast}:=\arg\min_{\Delta\theta_L}\Phi(\Delta\theta_L,0)$.
Then the optimal conditional update of the upper segment given the stage-1 lower update is
\begin{equation}
\Delta_H^{\ast}\ =\ -B^{-1}C^\top \Delta_L^{\ast},
\label{eq:deltaH_star}
\end{equation}
and the resulting proxy decrease from performing stage 2 (relative to stopping after stage 1) is
\begin{equation}
\Phi(\Delta_L^{\ast},0)-\Phi(\Delta_L^{\ast},\Delta_H^{\ast})
\ =\
\frac12 \big\|B^{-1/2}C^\top \Delta_L^{\ast}\big\|_2^2.
\label{eq:two_stage_gain_rewrite}
\end{equation}
\end{proposition}
\noindent
Proposition~\ref{prop:two_stage_rewrite} does \emph{not} claim that two-stage improves the oracle optimum compared to jointly optimizing $(\Delta\theta_L,\Delta\theta_H)$.
Instead, it isolates a coupling-induced correction term that the second stage captures explicitly.
This motivates two-stage schedules as a practical solver: when the segments are coupled ($C\neq 0$), staged optimization can
reduce optimization difficulty (e.g., sensitivity to learning rates or noisy gradients) by stabilizing one segment before adapting the other.
We empirically evaluate this as improved attainable performance and generalization at matched drift.

