\section{Near-Reference Drift-Budgeted SFT and Why LST Works}
\label{sec:nearref_lst}
We study \emph{drift-budgeted SFT}: improve a target SFT objective while keeping the adapted model near a strong reference checkpoint $\theta_0$.
Let
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y^*)\sim\mathcal{D}}[-\log \pi_{\theta}(y^*|x)]
\label{eq:tsft}
\end{equation}
and measure functional drift by
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{x}\Big[\mathrm{KL}\big(\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x)\ \|\ \pi_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x)\big)\Big].
\label{eq:dref}
\end{equation}
Near-reference adaptation can be viewed through the drift-budgeted objective
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta\in\Theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\qquad \text{s.t.}\qquad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,
\label{eq:budgeted_problem}
\end{equation}
where $\Theta$ is an \emph{update class} encoding which parameters are allowed to change.
This section focuses on the update class $\Theta$ induced by \emph{layer-selective tuning (LST)}.
The key reason LST is well-suited to \eqref{eq:budgeted_problem} is that, under small-drift geometry, it yields a
closed-form notion of \emph{best improvement per unit drift} and a corresponding, explicit \emph{restriction gap} that upper-bounds what LST can lose.
\subsection{Update class: LST}
\label{subsec:lst_def}
Let $M$ be a set of trainable layers/blocks. LST restricts updates to $M$:
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\neg M}\ \equiv\ \theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_constraint}
\end{equation}
\subsection{Local drift geometry and drift-normalized improvement}
\label{subsec:lst_local_geometry}
In a small neighborhood of $\theta_0$, KL drift induces a Fisher quadratic form.
Let $F$ denote the Fisher information matrix of $\pi_{\theta_0}$ (under the same input distribution as \eqref{eq:dref}).
\begin{lemma}[Local quadratic drift under LST]
\label{lem:kl_fisher_lst}
For $\theta=\theta_0+\Delta\theta$ in a sufficiently small neighborhood of $\theta_0$,
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta^\top F\,\Delta\theta.
\label{eq:kl_fisher}
\end{equation}
Under LST ($\Delta\theta_{\neg M}=0$),
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta_M)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\,\Delta\theta_M,
\label{eq:kl_fisher_restricted}
\end{equation}
where $F_M:=F_{MM}$.
\end{lemma}
Lemma~\ref{lem:kl_fisher_lst} turns the drift budget into a local ellipsoidal constraint in the trainable coordinates.
Let $g:=\nabla\mathcal{T}(\theta)\vert_{\theta_0}$ and $g_M$ its restriction to $M$.
\begin{lemma}[Best first-order SFT improvement at a given drift budget (within LST)]
\label{lem:budgeted_improvement}
Assume $F_M+\lambda I\succ 0$ for some damping $\lambda\ge 0$.
Consider the local drift-budgeted subproblem within the LST subspace:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Delta\theta_M}\ g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top (F_M+\lambda I)\Delta\theta_M\le \delta.
\label{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\end{equation}
Its optimal value is
\begin{equation}
\min \eqref{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\ =\
-\sqrt{2\delta}\,\|g_M\|_{(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}},
\label{eq:local_improvement_value}
\end{equation}
achieved by $\Delta\theta_M \propto -(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}g_M$.
\end{lemma}
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} makes the advantage of LST explicit:
for each candidate subset $M$, the near-reference improvement achievable per unit drift admits a closed form.
This directly supports subset selection: choose $M$ that maximizes the drift-normalized signal
$\|g_M\|_{(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}}$ (or its practical proxy).
\subsection{Where the loss can come from: an explicit upper bound via restriction gap}
\label{subsec:restriction_gap_bound}
The same drift-budgeted problem \eqref{eq:budgeted_problem} defines an \emph{oracle} optimum within the chosen update class.
Let
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)
:=
\min_{\theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,\ \theta_{\neg M}=\theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_oracle_opt}
\end{equation}
For any trained checkpoint $\hat\theta(M)$ satisfying $D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\hat\theta(M))\le \delta$, define the (restricted) optimization error
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{OptErr}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\hat\theta(M);\delta)
:=
\mathcal{T}(\hat\theta(M))-\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)\ \ge 0.
\label{eq:opterr_lst}
\end{equation}
Eq.~\eqref{eq:opterr_lst} identifies the only way LST can be ``worse than it could be'' at a fixed drift budget:
it is an \emph{optimization} issue rather than an unbounded accumulation issue.
Moreover, in the small-drift regime, Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} implies that the leading-order achievable improvement under LST is governed by
$\|g_M\|_{(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}}$; hence the \emph{restriction-induced} loss at budget $\delta$ is controlled (to first order) by how much of the drift-efficient
descent direction is captured by $M$.
This provides a concrete, budget-aligned notion of where performance may be lost, and motivates tightening the update class further to remove solver-dependent degrees of freedom.
\subsection{Anchored-LST: removing endpoint degrees of freedom}
\label{subsec:anchored_lst}
In practice, additional parameter freedoms at the input/output endpoints can obscure drift comparability across $M$ and introduce solver-dependent variability.
We therefore consider \emph{anchored-LST}, which freezes the input embedding and output projection (LM head) and selects $M$ only from transformer blocks.
The anchored setting admits drift diagnostics in a fixed readout basis and supports stable matched-drift subset selection; we detail this next.

