\section{Near-Reference Drift-Budgeted SFT and Layer-Selective Tuning}
\label{sec:nearref_lst}
We study a regime of \emph{near-reference drift-budgeted SFT}: improving a target supervised objective while limiting functional drift from a strong reference checkpoint $\theta_0$.
Let $\pi_\theta(\cdot|x)$ denote the model distribution over outputs given input $x$.
We consider supervised fine-tuning (SFT) with dataset $\mathcal D$,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y^*)\sim\mathcal{D}}[-\log \pi_{\theta}(y^*|x)],
\label{eq:tsft_def}
\end{equation}
and measure functional drift from the reference model via
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{x}\Big[\mathrm{KL}\big(\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x)\ \|\ \pi_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x)\big)\Big].
\label{eq:dref_def}
\end{equation}
A drift-budgeted view of near-reference SFT is
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta\in\Theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\qquad \text{s.t.}\qquad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,
\label{eq:drift_budget_problem}
\end{equation}
where $\Theta$ denotes an \emph{update class} that encodes which parameters are allowed to change.
In practice, the budget can be enforced implicitly (e.g., monitoring drift and early stopping).
\subsection{Update classes and the focus on coordinate restriction}
\label{subsec:update_classes}
Eq.~\eqref{eq:drift_budget_problem} separates the task objective from the \emph{parameterization of feasible updates}.
Common update classes include: (i) full-parameter tuning, (ii) coordinate restriction (a subset of original parameters is trainable),
and (iii) parameter expansion (auxiliary modules).
We focus on coordinate restriction because it preserves the original parameterization and yields a direct local geometry under KL drift.
Within this family, layer-selective tuning (LST) provides a natural granularity for controlling and diagnosing drift.
\subsection{Layer-selective tuning (LST)}
\label{subsec:lst}
Let $M$ be a set of trainable layers/blocks. LST restricts updates to $M$ by freezing the remaining parameters:
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\neg M}\ \equiv\ \theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_constraint}
\end{equation}
We analyze LST in the near-reference regime using the local geometry induced by $D_{\mathrm{ref}}$.
\subsection{Local drift geometry and drift-normalized improvement under LST}
\label{subsec:lst_local_geometry}
Around $\theta_0$, KL drift induces a Fisher quadratic form.
Let $F$ denote the Fisher information matrix of $\pi_{\theta_0}$ under the same input distribution as Eq.~\eqref{eq:dref_def}.
\begin{lemma}[Local quadratic approximation of KL drift]
\label{lem:kl_fisher}
For $\theta=\theta_0+\Delta\theta$ in a sufficiently small neighborhood of $\theta_0$,
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta^\top F\,\Delta\theta.
\label{eq:kl_fisher_quadratic}
\end{equation}
Under LST ($\Delta\theta_{\neg M}=0$),
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta_M)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\,\Delta\theta_M,
\label{eq:kl_fisher_quadratic_restricted}
\end{equation}
where $F_M:=F_{MM}$ is the principal submatrix restricted to coordinates in $M$.
\end{lemma}
Lemma~\ref{lem:kl_fisher} turns the drift budget into a local ellipsoidal constraint in the trainable coordinates.
Let $g:=\nabla\mathcal{T}(\theta)\vert_{\theta_0}$ and $g_M$ its restriction to $M$.
\begin{lemma}[Best first-order SFT improvement at a given drift budget (within LST)]
\label{lem:budgeted_improvement}
Assume $F_M\succ 0$. Consider the local drift-budgeted subproblem within the LST subspace:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Delta\theta_M}\ g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\Delta\theta_M\le \delta.
\label{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\end{equation}
Its optimal value is
\begin{equation}
\min \eqref{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\ =\
-\sqrt{2\delta}\,\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}},
\qquad
\|\upsilon\|_{F_M^{-1}}^2 := \upsilon^\top F_M^{-1}\upsilon,
\label{eq:local_improvement_value}
\end{equation}
achieved by $\Delta\theta_M \propto -F_M^{-1}g_M$.
\end{lemma}
\paragraph{Practical note (damping).}
In large models $F_M$ can be singular or ill-conditioned. In practice we use a damped metric $(F_M+\lambda I)$ and replace
$F_M^{-1}$ by $(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}$ (or a pseudoinverse), which preserves the drift-normalized interpretation while ensuring numerical well-posedness.
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} yields a concrete reason LST is well matched to drift-budgeted SFT:
for each candidate subset $M$, the best near-reference improvement per unit drift admits a closed form,
enabling principled subset selection via the drift-normalized signal $\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}}$ (or its proxy).
\subsection{Decomposing performance limits: restriction gap vs.\ optimization error}
\label{subsec:restriction_vs_optimization}
Under a fixed drift budget, LST performance is limited by two conceptually distinct factors.
\paragraph{(i) Subset-dependent limitation (restriction gap / approximation capacity).}
Even with an ideal solver, restricting updates to $M$ limits which drift-efficient descent directions are reachable.
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} quantifies this \emph{subset capacity} in the near-reference regime:
the best first-order decrease achievable under drift budget $\delta$ within $M$ scales with $\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}}$ (or its damped counterpart).
If $M$ fails to capture the drift-efficient directions of the task gradient, then no training procedure confined to $M$
can achieve large improvement at small drift. This motivates subset selection.
\paragraph{(ii) Solver-dependent limitation (optimization error).}
Given a subset $M$, define the drift-budgeted oracle optimum within LST:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)
:=
\min_{\theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,\ \theta_{\neg M}=\theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_oracle_opt}
\end{equation}
For any trained checkpoint $\hat\theta(M)$ satisfying $D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\hat\theta(M))\le \delta$, the \emph{optimization error} is
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{OptErr}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\hat\theta(M);\delta)
:=
\mathcal{T}(\hat\theta(M))-\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)\ \ge 0.
\label{eq:opterr_lst}
\end{equation}
This term isolates the solver-dependent part: how close training gets to the best achievable performance within the chosen subset $M$
under the same drift budget. In later sections, two-stage schedules are introduced to reduce this optimization error for coupled segmental LST.
\paragraph{Summary.}
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} provides a drift-aligned signal for \emph{which subset} can be effective, while
Eq.~\eqref{eq:opterr_lst} characterizes \emph{how well} a given solver realizes that potential within the same drift budget.
\subsection{Anchored-LST: fixing endpoint degrees of freedom}
\label{subsec:anchored_lst}
In practice, endpoint parameterizations (input embedding and output projection) can introduce coordinate freedoms that obscure drift comparability across subsets and increase solver-dependent variability.
We therefore consider \emph{anchored-LST}, which freezes the input embedding and output projection (LM head) and selects $M$ only from transformer blocks.
Anchored-LST admits drift diagnostics in a fixed readout basis and supports stable matched-drift subset selection; we detail these diagnostics and the selection procedure next.

