\section{Method: Anchored-LST and Matched-Drift Selection}
\label{sec:subset_selection_drift}
Based on the theoretical framework in \S\ref{sec:nearref_lst_theory}, we propose a practical adaptation protocol.
We address the subset capacity limit via \emph{matched-drift selection} and the optimization error via a \emph{two-stage schedule},
all performed within an \emph{anchored} parameterization to ensure drift comparability.

\subsection{Anchored-LST: Removing endpoint gauge freedoms}
\label{subsec:anchored_lst_method}
To compare drift meaningfully across different subsets $M$, we must fix the coordinate system.
In decoder LMs, the output projection admits gauge transformations ($h \mapsto hA, W_{\mathrm{out}} \mapsto W_{\mathrm{out}}A^{-T}$) that preserve logits but alter parameter distance.
To eliminate these solver-dependent freedoms, we define \emph{Anchored-LST}: we freeze both the input embedding and the LM head, selecting $M$ only from transformer blocks.
This ensures drift measurements primarily reflect backbone changes.

\subsection{Practical Drift Diagnostics}
\label{subsec:drift_diagnostics}
With endpoints fixed, we measure drift in the fixed readout basis.
Let $p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)$ be the output distribution using the \emph{frozen} reference head.
We monitor drift on a probe set via
\begin{equation}
\widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
:=
\mathbb{E}_{x\in\mathcal{X}_{\mathrm{probe}},\,t}
\Big[
\mathrm{KL}\big(p^0_\theta(\cdot|x,t)\ \|\ p^0_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x,t)\big)
\Big].
\label{eq:D_ref_probe}
\end{equation}
(Optional) If the head were trainable, we would also define a dual-output drift $\widehat D_{\mathrm{dual}}$ to isolate head-specific changes.

\subsection{Matched-Drift Selection Algorithm}
\label{subsec:subset_selection}
To maximize subset capacity (Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement}) without computing the expensive inverse Fisher matrix,
we use an empirical search.
We compare candidate subsets by their validation improvement at a \emph{matched} drift budget $\delta$.
For each candidate $M$:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Run a short tuning trajectory starting from $\theta_0$.
    \item Stop at step $\tau(M) := \min\{k : \widehat D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta^{(k)})\ge \delta\}$.
    \item Assign score $\mathrm{Score}(M) = \mathcal{E}(\theta_0) - \mathcal{E}(\theta^{(\tau(M))})$.
\end{enumerate}
This procedure acts as a practical proxy for maximizing $\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}}$, selecting the subset that yields the steepest descent per unit drift.
We employ a coarse-to-fine search over contiguous block segments to make this efficient.

\subsection{Two-Stage Solver for Coupled Segments}
\label{subsec:two_stage_method}
Once $M$ is selected (typically two segments $M_{\mathrm{low}}\cup M_{\mathrm{high}}$), we employ a two-stage schedule to minimize optimization error.
We model the local objective with a quadratic proxy involving a curvature matrix $H_M$ and drift penalty $\beta F_M$.
Let the Hessian of the proxy be $\begin{psmallmatrix} A & C\\ C^\top & B\end{psmallmatrix}$.

\begin{proposition}[Coupling-induced correction]
\label{prop:two_stage_rewrite}
Let $\Delta_L^{\ast}$ be the optimal stage-1 update for the lower segment.
The optimal stage-2 update for the upper segment decomposes into:
\begin{equation}
\Delta_H^{\ast}
\ =\
\underbrace{-B^{-1}g_H}_{\text{direct update}}
\ +\
\underbrace{(-B^{-1}C^\top \Delta_L^{\ast})}_{\text{coupling correction}}.
\end{equation}
The gain from explicitly modeling the coupling correction (vs.\ ignoring it) is $\frac{1}{2}\|B^{-1/2}C^\top \Delta_L^{\ast}\|_2^2$.
\end{proposition}
\noindent
This confirms that the second stage explicitly compensates for the drift induced by the lower segment (via the coupling term $C$), thereby stabilizing the optimization trajectory and improving attainability.

