\section{Near-Reference Drift-Budgeted SFT: Theory}
\label{sec:nearref_lst_theory}
We study a regime of \emph{near-reference drift-budgeted supervised fine-tuning (SFT)}: we aim to improve a supervised objective while explicitly limiting \emph{function-space} drift from a strong reference checkpoint $\theta_0$.
Let $\pi_\theta(\cdot|x)$ denote the model distribution over outputs given input $x$.
Given an SFT dataset $\mathcal D$, we define the task loss
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{(x,y^*)\sim\mathcal{D}}[-\log \pi_{\theta}(y^*|x)].
\label{eq:tsft_def}
\end{equation}
We measure functional drift from $\theta_0$ by the expected KL divergence
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)
\ :=\
\mathbb{E}_{x\sim\mu}\Big[\mathrm{KL}\big(\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x)\ \|\ \pi_{\theta_0}(\cdot|x)\big)\Big],
\label{eq:dref_def}
\end{equation}
where $\mu$ is a fixed input distribution (in practice approximated by a probe set; see \S\ref{subsec:drift_diagnostics}).
Our target problem is the drift-budgeted optimization
\begin{equation}
\min_{\theta\in\Theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\qquad \text{s.t.}\qquad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,
\label{eq:drift_budget_problem}
\end{equation}
where $\Theta$ denotes an \emph{update class} (the feasible set of parameter updates).
We focus on \emph{coordinate restriction} update classes because they preserve the original parameterization and yield a direct local geometry under KL drift.
In particular, we study \emph{layer-selective tuning (LST)}, which restricts updates to a subset of transformer blocks $M$ and freezes the rest:
\begin{equation}
\theta_{\neg M}\ \equiv\ \theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_constraint}
\end{equation}
This restriction yields a family of feasible sets indexed by $M$; our method will later select $M$ by comparing candidates at \emph{matched drift}.
\subsection{Local drift geometry and drift-normalized improvement}
\label{subsec:lst_local_geometry}
In a sufficiently small neighborhood of $\theta_0$, KL drift induces a Fisher quadratic form.
Let $F$ be the Fisher information matrix of $\pi_{\theta_0}$ under the same input distribution $\mu$ as in Eq.~\eqref{eq:dref_def}.
\begin{lemma}[Local quadratic approximation of KL drift]
\label{lem:kl_fisher}
For $\theta=\theta_0+\Delta\theta$ in a sufficiently small neighborhood of $\theta_0$,
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta^\top F\,\Delta\theta.
\label{eq:kl_fisher_quadratic}
\end{equation}
Under LST ($\Delta\theta_{\neg M}=0$),
\begin{equation}
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta_0+\Delta\theta_M)
\ \approx\
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\,\Delta\theta_M,
\label{eq:kl_fisher_quadratic_restricted}
\end{equation}
where $F_M:=F_{MM}$ is the principal submatrix on coordinates in $M$.
\end{lemma}
Lemma~\ref{lem:kl_fisher} turns the drift budget $D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le\delta$ into an (approximate) ellipsoidal constraint in the trainable coordinates.
Let $g := \nabla \mathcal{T}(\theta)\vert_{\theta_0}$ and $g_M$ its restriction to $M$.
\begin{lemma}[Best first-order SFT improvement within LST at a fixed drift budget]
\label{lem:budgeted_improvement}
Assume $F_M\succ 0$. Consider the local drift-budgeted subproblem within the LST subspace:
\begin{equation}
\min_{\Delta\theta_M}\ g_M^\top \Delta\theta_M
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
\frac{1}{2}\Delta\theta_M^\top F_M\Delta\theta_M\le \delta.
\label{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\end{equation}
Its optimal value is
\begin{equation}
\min \eqref{eq:local_trust_region_lst}
\ =\
-\sqrt{2\delta}\,\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}},
\qquad
\|\upsilon\|_{F_M^{-1}}^2 := \upsilon^\top F_M^{-1}\upsilon,
\label{eq:local_improvement_value}
\end{equation}
achieved by $\Delta\theta_M \propto -F_M^{-1}g_M$.
\end{lemma}
\paragraph{Practical note (damping).}
In large models, $F_M$ can be singular or ill-conditioned.
In practice we use a damped metric $(F_M+\lambda I)$ and replace $F_M^{-1}$ by $(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}$ (or a pseudoinverse).
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} implies that, in the near-reference regime, the \emph{subset-dependent potential} for improvement under a fixed drift budget is governed by the drift-normalized signal $\|g_M\|_{(F_M+\lambda I)^{-1}}$.
\subsection{Decomposing performance limits: subset capacity vs.\ optimization error}
\label{subsec:restriction_vs_optimization}
Under a fixed drift budget, LST performance is limited by two conceptually distinct factors.
\paragraph{(i) Subset capacity (restriction gap).}
Even with an ideal solver, restricting updates to $M$ limits which drift-efficient descent directions are reachable.
Lemma~\ref{lem:budgeted_improvement} quantifies this limitation in the near-reference regime: if $M$ does not capture drift-efficient components of the gradient, then $\|g_M\|_{F_M^{-1}}$ will be small, and no procedure confined to $M$ can achieve large improvement at small drift.
This motivates \emph{selecting} $M$ by comparing candidates at matched drift.
\paragraph{(ii) Optimization error (attainability within a subset).}
Fix a subset $M$. Define the oracle best achievable value within LST under budget $\delta$:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)
:=
\min_{\theta}\ \mathcal{T}(\theta)
\quad \text{s.t.}\quad
D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\theta)\le \delta,\ \theta_{\neg M}=\theta_{0,\neg M}.
\label{eq:lst_oracle_opt}
\end{equation}
For any trained checkpoint $\hat\theta(M)$ satisfying $D_{\mathrm{ref}}(\hat\theta(M))\le \delta$, the restricted optimization error is
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{OptErr}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\hat\theta(M);\delta)
:=
\mathcal{T}(\hat\theta(M))-\mathcal{T}^{\star}_{\mathrm{LST}}(\delta;M)\ \ge 0.
\label{eq:opterr_lst}
\end{equation}
This isolates solver-dependent limitations: how close training gets to the subset-dependent oracle within the same drift budget.
\paragraph{Preview of the method.}
Our method addresses these two limitations separately:
(1) we choose $M$ via \emph{matched-drift subset selection}, a black-box proxy for drift-normalized improvement; and
(2) once $M$ is fixed, we reduce $\mathrm{OptErr}_{\mathrm{LST}}$ using a two-stage schedule designed to absorb cross-segment coupling.
